Subqueries and Correlated queries
🧠 1. What is a Subquery?
👉 A subquery = query inside another query
Think:
> “First get some data → then use it in main query”

🔹 Basic Structure
SELECT column
FROM table
WHERE column = (SELECT something FROM table);

📘 Example Table: students
id	name	age	marks
1	Rahul	22	80
2	Amit	19	70
3	Neha	21	90
4	Ravi	22	60

🔹 Example 1: Find student with highest marks
SELECT name
FROM students
WHERE marks = (SELECT MAX(marks) FROM students);

🧠 How it works
Step 1:
SELECT MAX(marks) FROM students;
👉 returns 90
Step 2:
WHERE marks = 90
👉 Final answer: Neha

🔹 Example 2: Students above average
SELECT name
FROM students
WHERE marks > (SELECT AVG(marks) FROM students);

🧠 Types of Subqueries
1. Single Row Subquery
👉 Returns one value (MAX, AVG)

2. Multiple Row Subquery
SELECT name
FROM students
WHERE age IN (SELECT age FROM students WHERE age > 20);

3. Subquery in SELECT
SELECT name,
(SELECT AVG(marks) FROM students) AS avg_marks
FROM students;
⚠️ Common Mistake
❌ Using = with multiple values:
WHERE age = (SELECT age FROM students);
👉 Error
✅ Use:
WHERE age IN (SELECT age FROM students);
---
🔥 2. Correlated Subquery (Very Important 🔥🔥)
👉 A subquery that runs for each row of outer query

🧠 Simple Meaning
👉 “Outer query sends value → inner query uses it”

🔹 Example: Students above their class average
Table:
name	class	marks
Rahul	A	80
Amit	A	70
Neha	B	90
Ravi	B	60

🔹 Query
SELECT name
FROM students s
WHERE marks > (
  SELECT AVG(marks)
  FROM students
  WHERE class = s.class
);

🧠 How it works
For each student:
Take their class
Find average of that class
Compare marks

👉 Output:
name
Rahul
Neha

🔁 Difference: Subquery vs Correlated
Feature	Subquery	Correlated
Runs	             Once	             For each row
Speed	             Faster	             Slower
Dependency	Independent	Depends on outer query

🔥 Real-Life Use Cases
Employees earning more than dept average
Customers with orders above average
Students above class average

🧪 Advanced Example (Interview Level)
🔹 Find employees with salary > department avg
SELECT name
FROM employees e
WHERE salary > (
  SELECT AVG(salary)
  FROM employees
  WHERE dept_id = e.dept_id
);

⚠️ Performance Tip
👉 Correlated queries are slow
👉 In real projects → often replaced by JOIN or window functions
